19 Art. 312. Right to bail before and after conviction
20 A. Except as provided in this Article and, Article 312.1, Article 313, or
21 Article 313.1, a person in custody who is charged with the commission of an offense
22 is entitled to bail before conviction.
23 B.(1) A person released on a previously posted bail undertaking for any of
24 the following shall not be readmitted to bail when the person previously failed
25 to appear and a warrant for arrest was issued and not recalled or the previous
26 bail undertaking has been revoked or forfeited:
27 (1) a (a) A crime of violence as defined by R.S. 14:2(B) which carries a
28 minimum mandatory sentence of imprisonment upon conviction or.
29 (2) the (b) The production, manufacture, distribution, or dispensing or
30 possession with intent to produce, manufacture, distribute, or dispense a controlled
31 dangerous substance as defined by the Louisiana Uniform Controlled Dangerous
32 Substances Law, shall not be readmitted to bail when the person previously failed to
33 appear and a warrant for arrest was issued and not recalled or the previous bail
34 undertaking has been revoked or forfeited.
35 (c) Any offense involving the possession or use of a firearm.
36 (d) Any sex offense as defined by R.S. 15:541.
37 (2) If a person voluntarily appears without confinement by a law
38 enforcement officer or bail recovery agent following a motion to revoke bail or
39 issuance of an arrest warrant for failure to appear but prior to revocation or
40 forfeiture, then he may be released only under one of the following circumstances:
41 (1)(a) After a contradictory hearing, a person may be released on the
42 previously posted bail undertaking if the motion to revoke bail is rescinded or the
43 arrest warrant is recalled and the surety is present or represented at the hearing and
44 gives written consent. Previous instances of revocation and forfeiture in unrelated
45 cases are admissible at the hearing. This relief is available only once.
