34 Art. 312.1. Revocation of bail upon subsequent felony arrest
35 A. If a defendant is admitted to bail for any crime of violence, any sex
36 offense, or any crime involving the possession or use of a firearm, the bail for
37 such offense shall be revoked upon any subsequent arrest for a felony offense
38 that is not a part of the same transaction, occurrence, or criminal episode which
39 resulted in the arrest that is the basis for the defendant's current admittance to
40 bail.
41 B.(1) Prior to booking the defendant, the arresting agency shall conduct
42 a prompt and diligent search to determine if the defendant is currently on bail
43 for any crime of violence, any sex offense, or any crime involving the possession
44 or use of a firearm.
45 (2) The arresting agency shall provide the court with the information
46 described in Subparagraph (1) of this Paragraph, along with an updated
47 criminal history with all other booking information, for the court to consider
48 when determining the defendant's entitlement to bail, the amount of bail, and
49 conditions of bail.
50 C. If the court determines that the defendant is currently on bail for any
51 crime of violence, any sex offense, or any crime involving the possession or use
52 of a firearm, the bail for such offense shall be revoked upon any subsequent
53 arrest for a felony offense that is not a part of the same transaction, occurrence,
54 or criminal episode which resulted in the arrest that is the basis for the
55 defendant's current admittance to bail. The court shall enter an order revoking
56 such prior bail, pending a bail hearing which may be invoked by the state or the
57 defendant. Either party may seek supervisory review of the granting or denial
58 of any order that revokes the defendant's prior admittance to bail.
